<Layout title="Preparing Your Brisbane Investment Property for Sale: A Landlord's Checklist | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Selling a tenanted Brisbane investment property requires a different approach to an owner-occupied sale. Here is the step-by-step checklist for landlords, from the first decision to settlement." draft={draft}>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Preparing Your Brisbane Investment Property for Sale: A Landlord's Checklist
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling a tenanted property is different to selling an owner-occupied home. Your control over presentation is limited by your tenant's rights, and the buyer pool may be different. Here is the process that gets landlords to a clean, well-positioned sale.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Investment property sales require a different preparation approach to owner-occupied sales, and the difference starts before you contact an agent. A landlord selling in Brisbane's inner east is making decisions about tenant management, access, presentation, and buyer targeting that an owner-occupier never has to think about. Getting these decisions right early avoids the friction that can delay a campaign or reduce the price you achieve.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step 1: Decide whether to sell with the tenant in place or seek vacant possession</h2>
      <p>This is the first and most consequential decision. It shapes everything that follows: your buyer pool, your campaign strategy, your presentation options, and your timeline.</p>

      <p><strong>Selling with the tenant in place</strong> means you market the property as a ready-to-go investment. Your buyers are investors seeking yield, and the selling points are the current rent, the tenancy history, and the management setup. You do not need to wait for the tenancy to end, and you do not lose rental income during the campaign. The trade-off is that your presentation is limited by what a tenant's home looks like during a sales campaign, and owner-occupiers are largely excluded from your buyer pool.</p>

      <p><strong>Vacant possession</strong> opens the property to owner-occupiers and investors who want to set their own tenancy terms. Presentation can be managed fully: styling, photography on your timeline, and inspections without coordinating around a tenant's schedule. The trade-offs are that you need to give the tenant proper notice under the <em>Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008</em> (Qld), which may be a lengthy process depending on whether the tenancy is periodic or fixed term, and you will lose rental income for the period between the tenant vacating and settlement.</p>

      <p>Neither approach is universally better. The right answer depends on your property's appeal to owner-occupiers, the strength of the current rent relative to market, the tenant's cooperation, and the timing of the tenancy end date.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step 2: Brief your property manager before contacting an agent</h2>
      <p>Your property manager manages the relationship with the tenant, and their cooperation with the sales process depends on that relationship being maintained professionally. Brief your PM on your intention to sell before any other action. They will advise on the notice requirements for the tenancy, coordinate access for inspections and photography, and manage the tenant's expectations through the campaign.</p>

      <p>The PM also holds documents you will need: the current lease, rent receipts, and maintenance records. If you are selling with the tenant in place, the buyer's solicitor will request the lease as part of due diligence. Having it ready from day one avoids delays.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step 3: Gather the financial and tenancy documents</h2>
      <p>Investor buyers want to see the numbers before they inspect. Having this documentation ready at the start of the campaign signals that you are a prepared vendor and reduces the back-and-forth that slows negotiations. The documents to prepare:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>Current lease agreement (showing rent, term, and review date)</li>
        <li>Rental payment history for the past 12 months</li>
        <li>Current rental appraisal from the property manager</li>
        <li>Body corporate disclosure statement (if unit or townhouse)</li>
        <li>Depreciation schedule if one exists</li>
        <li>Records of maintenance work carried out in the past 12 months</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step 4: Inspect and address deferred maintenance</h2>
      <p>Arrange a property inspection with proper notice to the tenant (minimum 24 hours under Queensland law for a routine inspection). Walk through the property as if you are a buyer conducting a building and pest inspection. Items that a B&P report will flag give buyers the confidence to negotiate hard on price. Minor maintenance that costs a few hundred dollars to fix can cost thousands at negotiation.</p>

      <p>The items worth addressing before campaign: leaking tap washers, faulty smoke alarms (check compliance as described in step 7), stiff or broken door and window hardware, deteriorating silicone in wet areas, and any obvious roof or gutter issues visible from ground level. Structural defects and significant repairs are a different matter and require a different conversation with your agent about pricing strategy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step 5: Coordinate photography carefully</h2>
      <p>Photography is where many tenanted investment sales lose value. Poor photography, produced because the property was photographed full of the tenant's belongings without proper coordination, creates listings that underperform from day one.</p>

      <p>Coordinate with your PM to brief the tenant on the photography appointment well in advance. The tenant has a right to a tidy, lived-in home, but most tenants will cooperate with reasonable requests to clear benchtops, tidy living areas, and ensure pets are out of the property during the shoot. A professional photographer who works regularly with investment properties knows how to maximise what they have. If the property is vacant, styling at least the key rooms (living, master bedroom, kitchen) adds more to buyer perception than its cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step 6: Prepare a one-page financial summary</h2>
      <p>This is the document that investor buyers read before they decide whether to inspect. It should fit on a single page and show:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>Current weekly rent and annual rental income</li>
        <li>Property management fee (percentage and dollar amount)</li>
        <li>Council rates (annual)</li>
        <li>Building and landlord insurance</li>
        <li>Body corporate levies if applicable (admin fund and sinking fund separately)</li>
        <li>Estimated net yield at asking price and at a range of alternative prices</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Do not include expenses you are unsure of or that vary significantly. A conservative, accurate summary is more useful to a buyer than an optimistic one that falls apart under scrutiny and damages trust mid-campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step 7: Confirm smoke alarm and pool compliance</h2>
      <p>Compliance obligations sit with the seller at the point of sale, not with the tenant. Regardless of the tenancy arrangements, you are required to confirm at settlement that the property meets Queensland's smoke alarm legislation and, if there is a pool, that a current pool safety certificate is in place (or that the alternative declaration option has been followed).</p>

      <p>Smoke alarm compliance for Queensland residential properties means interconnected photoelectric alarms on every storey, in every bedroom, and in hallways connecting bedrooms to the rest of the dwelling. For properties where the alarms were installed before the compliance deadline, confirm with an electrician or compliance specialist that the installation meets the current standard. Do not assume the alarms a tenant has been living with are compliant.</p>

      <p>For pool safety, the Queensland Building and Construction Commission maintains the register of certified pool safety inspectors. If your certificate has expired, arrange a new inspection before you list. Discovering a pool compliance issue mid-campaign creates unnecessary pressure and can give buyers grounds to renegotiate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pulling it together</h2>
      <p>The landlords who achieve the strongest results are the ones who treat the preparation phase as seriously as owner-occupiers do. The constraints are different, but the principle is the same: buyers are more confident, and therefore more competitive, when the property is presented well, the documentation is complete, and the compliance items are resolved before they ever attend an inspection. Starting this process two to three months before you intend to list gives you enough time to work through the steps without pressure.</p>

